# Schedule polls — no min/max date constraint

The organizer can propose **any number of dates** when creating a game-night poll
(1, 2, 5, 10 — whatever they want). This is an explicit product decision per
the user.

## What is allowed

- A poll with a single proposed date (no real "voting between dates" — just
  yes/no/maybe on that one date).
- A poll with many dates (e.g. 8+ across multiple weeks).

## What MUST NOT be reintroduced

Do **NOT** add any of the following without explicit user request:

| Layer | Forbidden |
|---|---|
| Client (`CreatePollModal` in `src/components/ScheduleTab.tsx`) | `MIN_DATES`, `MAX_DATES`, `length >= N` guards on `addDate`, validation rejecting `length < N` or `length > N`, hint text mentioning "at least 2" or "up to 5" |
| Server (`create_game_poll` RPC in `supabase/0**-schedule-*.sql`) | `IF v_date_count > N THEN RAISE EXCEPTION 'invalid_date_count'`, `BETWEEN n AND m` clauses, JSONB array length upper bounds |
| Translations (`src/i18n/translations.ts`) | `schedule.dateRangeMin`, `schedule.dateRangeMax`, "between 2 and 5" copy |

The **only** validation that may run on date count is "at least one date with
a real `proposedDate` value". Past-date and duplicate-date validation are
fine; a hard count cap is not.

## Why this rule exists

A previous implementation enforced "2 ≤ count ≤ 5" both in `CreatePollModal`
and in `create_game_poll`. Migration `026-schedule-flexible-date-count.sql`
removed the server-side cap; the client must remain consistent with that.
The user explicitly asked for the constraint to be removed and **not be
reintroduced**.

## When tempted to add a cap "for safety"

Don't. The trade-off has been considered and the answer is no.
If a future ask requires a soft cap (e.g. "warn after 10 dates"), surface it
as a non-blocking hint, never as a validation error or disabled button.
